04354nam a22005295i 9781554582822DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20082008xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545828227 a10.51644/97815545828222doi  a(DE-B1597)667249  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBT1392.A6372 7aREL0060702bisacsh04a229.941 aKaler, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFlora Tells a Story :bThe Apocalypse of Paul and Its Contexts /cMichael Kaler. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b11 b&w illustrations, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Christianity and Judaism ;v1900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tThe Text -- tFlora Tells a Story -- t“The Apocalypse of Paul is a text …” -- t“written in the late second or early third century by a gnostic (possibly Valentinian) author …” -- t“showing the apostle Paul …” -- t“as an apocalyptic hero …” -- t“… in order to authoritatively present a gnostic understanding of the cosmos and the Pauline writings” -- tGeneral Conclusion -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndexes -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies in Religion / Corporation Canadienne des Sciences Religieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn early Christianity, many people were inspired to write gospels, treatises, letters, and stories celebrating the new faith, but not all of these writings are found in the New Testament. One such story from an unknown author is the Coptic, gnostic Apocalypse of Paul, a tale of the apostle Paul’s ascent to the heavens that was lost for millennia and rediscovered at Nag Hammadi in 1945. In Flora Tells a Story, Michael Kaler discusses the Apocalypse of Paul and how it was shaped by its literary environment. The book takes a behind the scenes look at early Christian literary production, analyzing the ways in which various literary traditions—such as apocalyptic writings, gnostic thought, and understandings of Paul—influenced the author of the Apocalypse of Paul and helped to shape the text. It also includes a new annotated English translation of the Apocalypse of Paul and a fictional account of how it might have come to be written. This work is the most in-depth study of the Apocalypse of Paul to date and the only full-length discussion of it in English. It provides a detailed but accessible account of the literary environment in which its author worked and integrates this little-known work into the broader stream of early Christian writings. This book will be of interest to specialists in Nag Hammadi and gnostic studies and early Christian literature, but will also appeal to the general reader interested in Christianity, mysticism, and gnosticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory: Jewish Studies. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Bible / Commentaries / New Testament.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458282240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554582822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554582822/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles